Section Summary: In 1820, the remains of a great city in Ancient Egypt were discovered in Middle Egypt, and in 1888, a number of clay tablets were found near the ruins of Tell el Amarna. The tablets, written in Babylonian cuneiform, were part of the Egyptian state archives during the reigns of Kings Amenophis III and IV, and consisted mainly of letters from Egyptian officials and Asiatic kings to the Egyptian monarch. The discovery revealed that the Semitic speech of Babylon was used as the language of diplomacy in the East around 1400 B.C. The Egyptian court and administration during this period were marked by a shift from a warlike spirit to a more peaceful and indulgent atmosphere under King Amenophis III, who reigned for 36 years. His son, Amenophis IV, attempted to reform the Egyptian religion, introducing a form of monotheism that worshipped the sun disk, symbol of the god Ra.
